litary reports and corporate marketing to human rights reports and poetry—amplify or diminish our capacity both to understand and to control what happens next? Contributors from anthropology, communications, criminology, global studies, law, literary and cultural studies, and women and gender studies bring diverse methodological approaches to these crucial questions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHuman rights. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspects. 4aCommunication : Communication. 4aPolitics and Law : Human Rights. 4aPolitics and Law : International Relations. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Sociology. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh1 aCingranelli, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDawes, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDaws, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDigangi, Elizabeth A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgan, Ulic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFilippov, Mikhail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrace, Jamie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHitchcock, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoenig, Alexa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKowal, Donna M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLesavoy, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMark, Brendan Skip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Alexandra S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Alexandra S., eeditor.4edt4http://